# üêû bug report

### Affected Package
 The issue is caused by HashLocationStrategy  in package @angular/common. Specifically the prepareExternalUrl function.


### Is this a regression?

Not that I am aware of.


### Description

HashLocationStrategy does not retain the query params in the URL when the application is initialised if the requested path is `''`.

For example the query params are dropped for the following:

- http://localhost:4200/?message=hello > http://localhost:4300/#/
- http://localhost:4200/index.html?message=hello > http://localhost:4300/#/

However the query params are retained for the following:

- localhost:4200/#/dashboard?message=hello

This is very surprising to me, I would like the query strings to be retained even when the application is requested without a path (or technically a fragment in this case).

Apologies if this is a feature request and not a bug. However it feels like a bug to me because the PathLocationStrategy does not behave in the same manner. You can verify this by turning off setting useHash to false in AppRoutingModule in my minimal reproduction.


## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

You can see a minimal reproduction at [stackblitz](https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-ivy-agczcd?file=src%2Fapp%2Fapp.component.html).

The top link drops the query params where as the bottom link retains the query params.


